status_message:
What are some ways that the average person can help support families who will be affected by upcoming deportations? For example, if the main breadwinner of a household gets deported? I know a few families who will be affected in this way.

Does anyone know if they're going to deport the undocumented parents of children who were born here? If so, what happens? Do they send the children back with them? What if they're in high school (or college but still dependent on their parents) and can get away when the deportation force get their parents? Do we need to have some quick solutions at the ready to help these kids? At minimum, we'll need to be prepared to tell them where to go for help. 

Short of legal help (expensive) and possibly breaking the law (we can't help if we're all in jail), let's brainstorm the ways the average American can get involved to help. Protesting is great -- let's keep doing it. Meanwhile, however, we need to have something in place for rapid action. We need quick action, not complicated processes.

Please share your ideas and I'll put together a list and get it published and shared far and wide. 

If you or someone you know will be affected by this, please offer your thoughts on what needs there will be. We need ideas for not just money because people who don't have money to give will want to help, too. 

image via Occupy Democrats
